<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06005017 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06005017 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Faced with the anguish of those unable to get medicines, companies in westernGermany agreed to pay hefty subsidies to discount drugs in former EastGermany, Labor Minister Norbert Bluem said Friday. He said the drug industrywill pay $1.5 billon through 1993 to allow a 55 percent discount.;    Thediscount went into effect with the New Year, but drug firms in western Germanyrefused to deliver most medicines to pharmacies in the east. Many pharmaciesin eastern Germany didn't open Wednesday but did Thursday.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GERMAN DRUG SUBSIDY GETS MEDICINE FLOWING  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Foreign News in Brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910105  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Saturday  </DAY><MONTH>  January  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  89  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Saturday January 5, 199100005017,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>